In Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom, the bat settlement has declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development, which affects their habitats and their loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flying papers and chemical treatment of some building materials, as well as attacks by pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
But because of their night hunting, their ears are more useful in catching prey than their eyes.
They use complex echo-location techniques to identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
